comment.undefined: The Acoustics object defines the noise criteria for an environments space, whether it's the prescribed ductwork velocity, the noise rating for the space or the dB level.
Equipment gains are defined as the amount of both latent and sensible heat contributed by specified equipment within the space (dishwasher, oven, etc)
Exhaust is indicative of the amount of air that should be extracted from a space based on the space type (eg laboratory, woodshop) or fixtures contained within the space (eg toilets, showers)

The fire protection attributes of a space are indicative of the hazard level of the space (which influences the sprinkler count), the sprinkler system type required, and the presence of combustible materials or sloped ceilings.
Infiltration gains are defined as the amount of heat or heat loss contributed by cracks in the exterior envelope of the building which allow unconditioned outside air to be introduced to the space
Lighting gains are defined as the amount of heat contributed by light fixtures
People gains are defined as the amount of both latent and sensible heat contributed by people based on their assumed activity level within the space (dancing, sitting, etc)
Plug gains are defined as the amount of sensible heat contributed by electrical receptacle/outlet loads
The plumbing attributes of a space are indicative of the amount of cold water, hot water and waste required by a space, as well as requirements for vent, floor drains, hose bibs or natural gas
Pollutant gains are defined as the amount of both latent and sensible heat contributed by pollutution sources.
A profile object represents a gain, thermostat or humdistat as conditions vary over a 24-hour period
Ventilation defines the amount of outside air that should be introduced to a space, which is typically based on the number of occupants breathing the air and the area of the space.
A Environment Profile Result object that can be added to a Simulation Result
A results object containing angle data.
A results object containing wind-direction data.
A collection of DateTimes associated with a time-series result.
A results object containing diffuse horizontal radiation data.
A results object containing direct normal radiation data.
A results object containing global horizontal radiation data.
A results object containing energy per unit area data.
A results object containing insolation data.
A results object containing energy per unit time data.
A results object containing power data.
A results object containing energy data.
Interface for all AnalysisResult objects.
A results object containing illuminance data.
A results object containing atmospheric pressure data.
A results object containing pressure data.
A results object containing humidity ratio data.
A results object containing ratio data.
A results object containing relative humidity data.
A results object containing enthalpy data.
A results object containing specific energy data.
A results object containing dew point temperature data.
A results object containing dry bulb temperature data.
A results object containing temperature data.
A results object containing mean radiant temperature data.
A results object containing sky temperature data.
A results object containing surface temperature data.
A results object containing Universal Thermal Climate Index data.
A results object containing wet bulb temperature data.
A collection of results associated with a point-in-time.
A results object containing velocity data.
A results object containing wind speed data
An Environment Simulation Result object
Base class for all discrete mesh element results, that is a result for an individual node. Stores all identifier information and how to sort the results in a collection
Full collection of discrete results for an AnalysisGrid for a specific Analysis.
Lux contains results for Lux analysis. Inherits from MeshElementResult which provides properties related to which node this Lux is recorded for
Required for some calculations, such as determining the convective heat transfer coefficient
Fragment containing gas material properties
Fragment containing solid material properties related to material
This fragment is used to define physical and thermal properties for a building surface
This fragment is used to define the north angle, GMT offset and year of construction for a building
Fragment containing the place (city) and name of the nearest weather station
Fragment containing the peak heating and peak cooling for a buildng
Fragment containing lighting, occupant and equipment view coefficient property
Fragment containing the F-factor and additional heat transfer construction property
Fragment containing red, green and blue light reflectance property
Fragment containing red, green, and blue light transmittance property
Fragment containing heating and cooling load
Fragment containing the origin context property such as Element ID or Type
Fragment containing geometric and thermal properties of a panel
Fragment containing thermal boundary context, colour, and surface direction properties
Fragment containing the lighting, occupant and equipment radiation amount
Fragment containing space analytical properties (e.g. domestic hot water supply, daylight factor, heating and cooling sizing method)
Fragment containing space context properties (e.g. is external facing, colour, connected elements)
A zone of the external faces of an Environment Mesh.
This building object is used for setting the location and building type, which is required for some environmental workflows
An environment object used to define an edge of an external boundary (e.g. the edge of an environmental panel or opening)
The main classification for a building (e.g. Office, Residential)
The type of cutout or hole in a building surface/panel (e.g. Window, Door, Rooflight)
The type of environmental surface (e.g. Wall, Floor, Roof)
The main use of a space (e.g. Classroom, Lobby, Open Office)
An environment object used to define a volumetric mesh.
A cutout or hole in a building surface/panel (e.g. Window, Door, Rooflight)
An environmental object used to define planar surfaces of a space (e.g. Wall, Floor, Roof)
A space object is an analytical depiction of a room defined by its environmental conditions (internal gains)
A self-contained unit of accommodation, that could contain smaller spaces
Defines the design options for Openings.

Defines a uniquely identifiable point on the Earth in standard global Latitude, Longitude and Elevation, coordinate system. Particularly useful for specifying local climate conditions for environmental analysis.
Represents a specific moment in time related to a specific location of Earth geometry. Used for obtaining solar positions for specific moments in time at specific points on Earth
An environment object used to define the position of the sun (in azimuth and elevation)
An environment object used to describe time for climate analysis

An AnalysisGrid is used to define an area in 3D space that should be analysed for a given set of results, e.g. daylighting levels, wind levels, heat indexes, etc. - an AnalysisGrid can be used to represent a measurable bit of the environment, including a void in a space, or it can be used to represent a mesh on a panel for analysis
0D finite element for environmental analysis. Node class contains positional information and is used to build AnalysisGrids and provide links between model geometry and analytical results.
Profiles depict the time period (hours per day, days per week) during which equipment is contributing heat to the space.

Hazard Type indicates the combustibility of the materials within the space (Light, Ordinary or Extra). The indication of hazard type also determines the density of sprinklers required within the space.

Sprinkler System Type indicates whether the system will need to accommodate spaces that are subject to freezing (dry system type, commonly used in loading docks and parking garages), spaces that contain materials that when on fire would be spread further by water (foam system type, commonly used in a diesel generator room), spaces that contain precious materials that would be ruined by a false trip of the sprinkler system (preaction, commonly used in art galleries.)
Profiles depict the time period (hours per day, days per week) during which infiltration is contributing to or causing a loss of heat to the space.
Profiles depict the time period (hours per day, days per week) during which the lighting gain is contributing heat to the space.
Profiles depict the time period (hours per day, days per week) during which people are contributing heat to the space.
Profiles depict the time period (hours per day, days per week) during which plug loads are contributing heat to the space.
Profiles depict the time period (hours per day, days per week) during which pollutants are contributing heat to the space.
Profile Type depicts the type of profile (OnOff (0 or 1), ModulatingPercentage (0.0-1.0), or Absolute (-10000 to +10000))
The unit measurement of the profile result from the Profile Result enum
The type of the profile result from the Profile Result enum
The type of simulation result from the Simulation Result enum
Interface for Results belonging to a particular object. The owning object is identified and correlated to the Results by its ID.

Base interface for all analytical results.
For expanded functionality, a result class should generally either implement the IResultItem or IResultCollection interface, or one of their sub-interfaces, rather than this interface directly.
Interface for results that correspond to a particular case.
Interface for results that correspond to a particular time step, for example a discrete result from a time history anlysis.
Base interface for results classes that are a collection of individual results, for example IMeshResults.
Required for some calculations, such as determining the convective heat transfer coefficient. Use Roughness enum
The type of gas (e.g Air, Argon). Use GasType enum
Required for some calculations, such as determining the convective heat transfer coefficient. Use Roughness enum
The cooling size method of the space. Use SizingMethod enum
The heating size method of the space. Use SizingMethod enum
The real-world Earth location for the building
The main classification for the building (e.g. Office, Residential). Use BuildingType enum)
A BHoM Geometry planar curve object (e.g polyline, line, etc.)
The interface for all one-dimensional geometrical objects.

Enables geometrical operations to be performed on a Curve based spatial element, whilst preserving all other object properties as unchanged. /nObjects implementing this interface will be required to implement some base methods for getting and setting data in a way that maintains the object's other properties.Documentation detailing required extension methods can be found here: https://github.com/BHoM/documentation/wiki/IElement-required-extension-methods

The common base interface for all the Spatial Dimensional Objects.This interface should not be implemented directly, only through its sub-interfaces.Methods operating on IElement assume a specific implementation of one or other of the sub-interfaces (i.e. IElement0D, IElement1D, IElement2D)
Defines the three-dimensional Mesh geometry.
A polygon mesh, defined by a list of triangular or quadrilateral Faces, Cells and their Vertices.
A construction object providing construction information about the frame of the opening
A construction object providing construction information about the opening - typically gazing construction
The type of opening on a panel (e.g. Window, Door). Use OpeningType enum

Enables geometrical operations to be performed on an edge curve based two-dimensional spatial element, whilst preserving all other object properties as unchanged. /nThe interface expects the outline to be constructed of IElement1D elements and allows for internal IElement2D elements.Objects implementing this interface will be required to implement some base methods for getting and setting data in a way that maintains the object's other properties.Documentation detailing required extension methods can be found here: https://github.com/BHoM/documentation/wiki/IElement-required-extension-methods

Enables Mass based operations to be performed on elements with materiality
Ensures the material composition of a physical object is represented, defined as proportions of discrete types of material forming the object's total solid volume.
Objects implementing this Interface will be required to implement some base methods for getting and setting data in a way that maintains the object's other properties.
Documentation detailing required extension methods can be found here: https://github.com/BHoM/documentation/wiki/IElement-required-extension-methods
A construction object providing layer and material information for the panel
The type of environmental surface (e.g. Wall, Floor, Roof). Use PanelType enum)

comment.undefined: Occupant Density is an object that defines the area occupied by each individual in a space (2 m2 per person).
Acoustics for an Environments Space define the noise within the space, by noise created by the velocity of the air within the ducts in the space, the Noise Rating, and decibel.
The plumbing attributes of a space are indicative of the amount of cold water, hot water and waste required by a space, as well as requirements for vent, floor drains, hose bibs or natural gas.

The fire protection attributes of a space are indicative of the hazard level of the space (which influences the sprinkler count), the sprinkler system type required, and the presence of combustible materials or sloped ceilings.
Space Type is an enum that defines how the space is used (Museum, Corridor, etc)
A point in 3D space providing a location point of the space
Defines a dimensionless location in three-dimensional space.
A 2D curve defining the external boundaries of the floor of the space
Base interface for analytical elements defined by a single closed perimiter curve.
A 2D curve defining the external boundaries of the floor of the region.
The type of opening that should be created from this opening configuration.
Describes the location of Earth geometry using the Location object which provides longitudal and latitudal data
Describes a specific moment in time
The BoundaryCurve is the outer-most edges of the AnalysisGrid. Nodes should not fall outside of this curve
A curve consisting of a continuous chain of straight line segments. The Polyline is considered closed if the first and last ControlPoints are coincident
Position of the node in global Cartesian 3D space.
